Black holes are regions in space where gravity is so strong that nothing, not even light, can escape from them. They are formed when a massive star runs out of fuel and collapses under its own gravity, compressing its mass into a very small and dense point known as a singularity. The boundary surrounding the singularity is called the event horizon, which marks the point of no return for anything that crosses it.

Black holes come in different sizes, with stellar black holes being formed from the remnants of massive stars and supermassive black holes existing at the centers of galaxies, containing millions or even billions of times the mass of our sun. Despite their mysterious nature, black holes play a crucial role in shaping the universe and are key objects of study in astrophysics.
